    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-25T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-25T17:00:00-05:00" n="837"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d837">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12586.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Vice Consul <persName type="to">Silliman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-25T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 25, 1914, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department has received information from Mexico City, under date of July 22 that
                    “situation here becoming dangerous on account <pb facs="0687" n="571"
                        xml:id="pg_571"/> of persistent daily attacks on places in the surroundings
                    of the capital and also because there are reasons to fear that the army might
                    revolt or disband at any moment incited by the publication of statements
                    attributed to Carranza that he will resort to reprisals and bloodshed upon
                    reaching Mexico and by fear that the arrangement for the transfer of power will
                    not provide sufficient guarantees for them.”</p>
                <p>You may use your own judgment as to whether this is an opportune moment to
                    suggest to Carranza the advisability of his issuing a frank statement calculated
                    to allay anxiety and inspire public confidence not only in Mexico City but
                    throughout the whole world.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
